    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="writingSession">
                <p><pb n="1r"/>I have not at hand the means of <lb/>verifying the calculations
                    contained in your note, <lb/>which after having shown to <choice>
                        <abbr>M.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi></abbr>
                        <expan>Mister</expan>
                    </choice> Gallatin, I have now <lb/>the pleasure to return. So far as the United
                    States <lb/>are concerned, the note which he has furnished, and <lb/>which is
                    enclosed, will enable you to fill the blank <lb/>left for the number of blacks
                    taken from Africa <lb/>to furnish the stock of those we possess. Has <lb/>not
                    the waste also been much less in the Spanish <lb/>and Portuguese colonies, than
                    in <add place="superlinear">these which remain in the hands of</add> the
                    English? <lb/><choice>
                        <orig>and</orig>
                        <reg>And</reg>
                    </choice> will not the rule of proportion drawn from <lb/>Jamaica, when applied
                    to them, be too great for <lb/>the number taken from Africa? If you have
                    <lb/>not good information, and recent, respecting Cuba, <lb/>I would suppose the
                    present number of slaves in <lb/>that islands rated too low. Since the trade has
                    <lb/>been kept open there (I believe 15 years) the annual <lb/>importation of
                    slaves has been very considerable, <lb/>and lately, at least 20,000 a year.</p>
                <p>You are perhaps aware that Colquhoun is <lb/><pb n="1v"/>a little given to
                    exaggeration and that his <lb/>calculations must be received with some
                    allowance.</p>
                <p>With the greatest considerations &amp; regard <lb/>I have the honor to be, my
                    dear Sir, <lb/>your most obedient servant <lb/>D. Sheldon <lb/><date>Friday 31
                        May</date></p>
                <p><pb n="2r"/><choice>
                        <abbr>M.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi></abbr>
                        <expan>Mister</expan>
                    </choice> Sheldon has the honor to enclose <lb/>the note respecting the
                    population of the United <lb/>States which he promised to <choice>
                        <abbr>M.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi></abbr>
                        <expan>Monsieur</expan>
                    </choice> de Humboldt. It <lb/>shows that the proportions between the sexes are
                    <lb/>nearly the same among the slaves as in the white <lb/>population. In the
                    free-colored population the <lb/>proportion of females is much greater; a
                    circumstance <lb/>doubtless owing to the greater number of females
                    <lb/>manumitted than of males. The females of this class <lb/>in the United
                    States, as probably every where else where <lb/>the mixed race exists, are the
                    most dissolute and least <lb/>productive portion of the population. Thus,
                    although <lb/>this class receives an increase by manumissions <lb/>continually,
                    its total increase is less than that of <lb/>any other; a striking proof of the
                    smaller number <lb/>of cildren produced by the women belonging to it. </p>
                <p><date>Tuesday 25.<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi> May</date></p>
                <p><pb n="2v"/>
                    <gap unit="pages" quantity="1" reason="empty"/></p>
                <p><pb n="3r"/>On comparing the result of this Census, with that of 1810, the
                    following proportions are found:</p>
                <p>
                    <table rows="4" cols="3">
                        <row>
                            <cell>The <hi rendition="#u">total</hi> population in 1810 was
                                7,239,903;</cell>
                            <cell>- in 1820, it was 9,625,547;</cell>
                            <cell>- increase 33 <choice>
                                    <abbr>p<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                                    <expan>percent</expan>
                                </choice>.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>The <hi rendition="#u">white</hi>
                                <choice>
                                    <abbr>popul.<hi rendition="#sup">n</hi></abbr>
                                    <expan>population</expan>
                                </choice> .. in 1810 was 5,862,093;</cell>
                            <cell>- in 1820, … 7,856,082;</cell>
                            <cell>- increase 34 <choice>
                                    <abbr>p<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                                    <expan>percent</expan>
                                </choice>.</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>The <hi rendition="#u">Slaves</hi> …. in 1810 were
                                1,191,364;</cell>
                            <cell>- in 1820, …. 1,531,436;</cell>
                            <cell>- increase 28 5/10 <choice>
                                    <abbr>p.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                                    <expan>percent</expan>
                                </choice>. <choice>
                                    <sic>*</sic>
                                    <corr type="deleted"/>
                                </choice></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>The <hi rendition="#u">free colored</hi>
                                <choice>
                                    <abbr>popul.<hi rendition="#sup">a</hi></abbr>
                                    <expan>population</expan>
                                </choice> in 1810 was 186,446;</cell>
                            <cell>- in 1820, …. 238,029;</cell>
                            <cell>- increase 27 2/3 <choice>
                                    <abbr>p<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                                    <expan>percent</expan>
                                </choice>.</cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                </p>
                <p>Although the increase of the <hi rendition="#u">white</hi> population throughout
                    the United States is 34 <choice>
                        <abbr>p<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                        <expan>percent</expan>
                    </choice>, <lb/>this population (the <hi rendition="#u">white</hi>) has
                    increased in the <hi rendition="#u">slave-states</hi> at a less rate than the
                        <hi rendition="#u">slave-<choice>
                            <abbr>populat<hi rendition="#sup">n</hi></abbr>
                            <expan>population</expan>
                        </choice></hi>
                    <lb/>in the same states. Thus, the <hi rendition="#u">white</hi> population in
                    those states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia,<lb/><note place="left"
                        hand="#Humboldt, Alexander von">tournez</note>: North-Carolina,
                    South-Carolina, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, Missouri, Kentucky,
                    <lb/>Tennessee, the Territory of <choice>
                        <orig>Arkansour</orig>
                        <reg>Arkansas</reg>
                    </choice>, and the Disctrict of Columbia) was in 1810, 2,208,785, and <lb/>in
                    1820, 2,825,391, making an increase of 28 <choice>
                        <abbr>p.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                        <expan>percent</expan>
                    </choice>, and at the same epochs, the <hi rendition="#u">slave-<choice>
                            <abbr>popul.<hi rendition="#sup">n</hi></abbr>
                            <expan>population</expan>
                        </choice></hi><lb/><note place="left" hand="#author"><hi rendition="#u"
                            >Cuba</hi></note>was 1,163,794, and 1,512,331 repectively, making an
                    increase of 30 <choice>
                        <abbr>p.<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>%</abbr>
                        <expan>percent</expan>
                    </choice>, a proof both that the <lb/>slaves are generally well-treated, and
                    that the climate is more congenial to them than to the whites. <lb/>The residue
                    of the slaves, constituting the whole slave-population of the United States, are
                    thinly scattered <lb/>through three or four of the other States, <gap
                        unit="words" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/> the remnants of those which
                    existed before slavery was <lb/>there abolished, and are yearly diminuishing in
                    numbers, theirchildren being born free.</p>
                <p><pb n="3v"/><choice>
                        <sic>Esclave</sic>
                        <corr cert="high">Esclaves</corr>
                    </choice> des <lb/>Étas Unis <lb/><hi rendition="#uu">Cuba</hi></p>
                <p>Souvent si mal <unclear reason="illegible" cert="high">imprimé</unclear>
                    <gap reason="lost" unit="words"/>
                    <lb/>exemple un vrai nombre 5,3 <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/><lb/>donne
                    5,308844. Seybert (<gap unit="words" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>
                    <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/>
                    <lb/>Mr Harvey <del rendition="#s">donne</del> (<gap reason="illegible"
                        unit="words" quantity="1"/> Phil<gap unit="words" reason="lost"/><lb/>5.309
                    758.</p>
                <p>Mr Harvey donne les <gap unit="chars" quantity="2" reason="illegible"/>
                    <gap reason="lost" unit="words"/><lb/>accroissement de la p<supplied cert="high"
                        >opulation</supplied>
                    <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/>
                    <lb/>
                    <gap unit="words" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>(p 41-55) <gap unit="words"
                        quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>
                    <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/>
                    <lb/>de 35, I. 36, I <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/><lb/>qui commence à <gap
                        unit="words" reason="lost"/>
                    <lb/>qui de 2 à 3 <gap unit="words" quantity="1" reason="illegible"/>
                    <lb/>de l'accroissement <gap unit="words" reason="lost"/></p>
                <p><pb n="4r"/>
                    <gap unit="pages" quantity="1" reason="empty"/></p>
                <p><pb n="4v"/><gap unit="pages" quantity="1" reason="empty"/></p>
            </div>
